{"title_page": "Richard Marggraf Turley", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Richard Marggraf Turley\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|8|2|df=yes}}\n| occupation  = Poet, literary critic}}\n\n'''Richard Marggraf Turley''' (born 2 August 1970) is a [[British people|British]] literary critic, poet and novelist. He specialises in Romanticism and the poetry of [[John Keats]], surveillance studies and ecocriticism. He is professor of English Literature at [[Aberystwyth University]], and between 2013 and 2018 was that institution's Professor of Engagement with the Public Imagination. \n\n==Life==\nMarggraf Turley was born in the [[Forest of Dean]]. He moved to Wales at the age of seven, was educated at [[King Henry VIII School, Abergavenny]], and read English at [[University of Leeds|Leeds University]].\n\n== Writer ==\nHe is author of three poetry collections: ''The Fossil Box'' (2007), concerned with the urgency of place and origins; ''Whiteout'' (2006), co-authored with Damian Walford Davies; and ''Wan-Hu's Flying Chair'' (2009), which won the 2010 [[Wales Book of the Year]] 'People's Choice' prize.\n\nIn 2007, he won first prize in the tenth-anniversary [[Keats-Shelley Prize for Poetry]]. His poem, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/donotmigrate/3668962/Elisions-by-Richard-Marggraf-Turley.html 'Elisions'], was written on the competition theme of slavery.\n\nIn 2010, together with Professor Reyer Zwiggelaar and Dr Bashar Rajoub of the Computer Science department at Aberystwyth University, Marggraf Turley conducted a 'Valentine's Day experiment' using thermal imaging cameras to determine whether reading love poetry produced distinct thermal signatures on the faces of volunteers.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2010/feb/13/valentines-love-poetry-hot-blood ''Guardian'' newspaper feature].</ref> \n\nIn March 2012, new research on Keats's ode 'To Autumn', co-authored with Dr Jayne Archer and Professor Howard Thomas (Aberystwyth University), was widely reported. Archival discoveries suggested that the 'stubble-plains' of Keats's ode '[[To Autumn]]' were located on St Giles's Hill, to the east of the City of Winchester, with implications for a new political reading of the poem. The part of St Giles's Hill in question now lies under a [[multi-storey car park]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/mar/23/john-keats-autumnal-idealist-social-commentator ''Guardian'' newspaper feature].</ref><ref>[http://blog.oup.com/2012/03/keats-ode-autumn-winchester-field/ Oxford University Press blog].</ref><ref>[http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/9613743.Keats__rural_idyll_now_a_car_park/ ''Southern Daily Echo''].</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2119109/Ode-NCP-How-cornfield-inspired-1819-poem-Keats-multi-storey-car-park.html ''Daily Mail'' newspaper feature].</ref> The editor of the Telegraph devoted 22 March 2012's editorial to an 'Ode to a Car Park'<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/9160657/Ode-to-a-Car-Park.html ''Telegraph'' editorial].</ref>\n\nIn 2013, research by Marggraf Turley, Archer and Thomas on the importance of Shakespeare's business dealings as a grain merchant for such plays as [[King Lear]] and [[Coriolanus]] was widely reported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-mid-wales-21993857|title=Shakespeare's past as food hoarder|date=2013-04-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bad-bard-a-tax-dodger-and-famine-profiteer-69qc5hrf2m3|title=Bad Bard: a tax dodger and famine profiteer|last=Leake|first=Jonathan|date=2013-03-31|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-01-15|issn=0956-1382}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2301829/Was-Shakespeare-tax-dodger-Bard-ruthless-businessman-exploited-famine-faced-jail-cheating-revenue.html|title=Was Shakespeare a tax dodger? Bard was 'ruthless businessman who exploited famine and faced jail for cheating revenue'|work=Mail Online|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref> Their work also threw light on the significance of crop weeds such as darnel in King Lear.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/food-blog/wales-food-security-shakespeare-keats-fiction|title=Can Shakespeare and Keats address today's food security challenges?|last=Balch|first=Oliver|date=2014-05-01|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref>\n\nMarggraf Turley has written a number of books on the [[Romantic poets]], including ''The Politics of Language in Romantic Literature'' (2002), ''Keats's Boyish Imagination'' (2004), ''Bright Stars: John Keats, Barry Cornwall and Romantic Literary Culture'' (2009), and ''Food and the Literary Imagination'', co-authored with Archer and Thomas (2015), and he is editor of ''Keats's Places'' (2018).\n\nHe is also author of a historical crime novel set in Romantic London of 1810, ''The Cunning House'' (2015).\n\nIn 2013, he was one of the three English-panel judges for the [[Wales Book of the Year]].\n\n== Poetry collections ==\n* 2009: ''Wan-Hu's Flying Chair'', Salt Press, {{ISBN|978-1844714438}}*\n* 2007: ''The Fossil-Box'', Cinnamon Press, {{ISBN|978-1-905614-35-6}} *\n* 2006: ''Whiteout'', co-authored with Damian Walford Davies, Parthian, {{ISBN|978-1-905762-15-6}}\n\n== Novel ==\n* 2015: ''The Cunning House'', Sandstone, {{ISBN|9781910124109}}\n\n== Critical studies ==\n* 2018: (ed.) ''Keats's Places'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|978-3319922423}}\n* 2015: (co-authored, Jayne Archer and Howard Thomas) ''Food and the Literary Imagination'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|978-1-137-40637-8}}\n* 2015: ''Writing Essays: A Guide for Students in English and the Humanities'', 2nd edn, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-1138916692}} \n* 2011: (ed.) ''The Writer in the Academy: Creative Interfrictions'', Boydell and Brewer, {{ISBN|978-1-84384-278-1}} \n* 2009: ''Bright Stars: Keats, Barry Cornwall and Romantic Literary Culture'', Liverpool University Press, {{ISBN|978-1-84631-211-3}} \n* 2006: (co-ed., Damian Walford Davies) ''The Monstrous Debt: Modalities of Romantic Influence in Twentieth-Century Literature'', Wayne State University Press, {{ISBN|978-0-8143-3058-6}} \n* 2004: ''Keats's Boyish Imagination'', Routledge, {{ISBN|978-0-415-28882-8}}  \n* 2002: ''The Politics of Language in Romantic Literature'', Palgrave Macmillan, {{ISBN|978-0-333-96898-7}}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* 2007: [[Keats-Shelley Prize for Poetry]]\n* 2010: [[Wales Book of the Year]] \"People's Choice\" award (sponsored by [[Media Wales]])\n* 2015: ASLE/Inspire-UKI Prize Essay (with Jayne Archer and Howard Thomas)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/donotmigrate/3668962/Elisions-by-Richard-Marggraf-Turley.html Richard Marggraf Turley's poem, \"Elisions], ''The Telegraph'' \n* [https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/english/staff-profiles/listing/profile/rcm University profile ]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marggraf Turley, Richard}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British poets]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Academics of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:British literary critics]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Richard Marggraf Turley\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|8|2|df=yes}}\n| occupation  = Poet, literary critic}}\n\n'''Richard Marggraf Turley''' (born 2 August 1970) is a [[British people|British]] literary critic, poet and novelist. He specialises in Romanticism and the poetry of [[John Keats]], surveillance studies and ecocriticism. He is professor of English Literature at [[Aberystwyth University]], and between 2013 and 2018 was that institution's Professor of Engagement with the Public Imagination. \n\n==Life==\nMarggraf Turley was born in the [[Forest of Dean]]. He moved to Wales at the age of seven, was educated at [[King Henry VIII School, Abergavenny]], and read English at [[University of Leeds|Leeds University]].\n\n== Writer ==\nHe is author of three poetry collections: ''The Fossil Box'' (2007), concerned with the urgency of place and origins; ''Whiteout'' (2006), co-authored with Damian Walford Davies; and ''Wan-Hu's Flying Chair'' (2009), which won the 2010 [[Wales Book of the Year]] 'People's Choice' prize.\n\nIn 2007, he won first prize in the tenth-anniversary [[Keats-Shelley Prize for Poetry]]. His poem, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/donotmigrate/3668962/Elisions-by-Richard-Marggraf-Turley.html 'Elisions'], was written on the competition theme of slavery.\n\nIn 2010, together with Professor Reyer Zwiggelaar and Dr Bashar Rajoub of the Computer Science department at Aberystwyth University, Marggraf Turley conducted a 'Valentine's Day experiment' using thermal imaging cameras to determine whether reading love poetry produced distinct thermal signatures on the faces of volunteers.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2010/feb/13/valentines-love-poetry-hot-blood ''Guardian'' newspaper feature].</ref> \n\nIn March 2012, new research on Keats's ode 'To Autumn', co-authored with Dr Jayne Archer and Professor Howard Thomas (Aberystwyth University), was widely reported. Archival discoveries suggested that the 'stubble-plains' of Keats's ode '[[To Autumn]]' were located on St Giles's Hill, to the east of the City of Winchester, with implications for a new political reading of the poem. The part of St Giles's Hill in question now lies under a [[multi-storey car park]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/mar/23/john-keats-autumnal-idealist-social-commentator ''Guardian'' newspaper feature].</ref><ref>[http://blog.oup.com/2012/03/keats-ode-autumn-winchester-field/ Oxford University Press blog].</ref><ref>[http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/9613743.Keats__rural_idyll_now_a_car_park/ ''Southern Daily Echo''].</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2119109/Ode-NCP-How-cornfield-inspired-1819-poem-Keats-multi-storey-car-park.html ''Daily Mail'' newspaper feature].</ref> The editor of the Telegraph devoted 22 March 2012's editorial to an 'Ode to a Car Park'<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/9160657/Ode-to-a-Car-Park.html ''Telegraph'' editorial].</ref>\n\nIn 2013, research by Marggraf Turley, Archer and Thomas on the importance of Shakespeare's business dealings as a grain merchant for such plays as [[King Lear]] and [[Coriolanus]] was widely reported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-mid-wales-21993857|title=Shakespeare's past as food hoarder|date=2013-04-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bad-bard-a-tax-dodger-and-famine-profiteer-69qc5hrf2m3|title=Bad Bard: a tax dodger and famine profiteer|last=Leake|first=Jonathan|date=2013-03-31|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-01-15|issn=0956-1382}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2301829/Was-Shakespeare-tax-dodger-Bard-ruthless-businessman-exploited-famine-faced-jail-cheating-revenue.html|title=Was Shakespeare a tax dodger? Bard was 'ruthless businessman who exploited famine and faced jail for cheating revenue'|work=Mail Online|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref> Their work also threw light on the significance of crop weeds such as darnel in King Lear.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/food-blog/wales-food-security-shakespeare-keats-fiction|title=Can Shakespeare and Keats address today's food security challenges?|last=Balch|first=Oliver|date=2014-05-01|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref>\n\nMarggraf Turley has written a number of books on the [[Romantic poets]], including ''The Politics of Language in Romantic Literature'' (2002), ''Keats's Boyish Imagination'' (2004), ''Bright Stars: John Keats, Barry Cornwall and Romantic Literary Culture'' (2009), and ''Food and the Literary Imagination'', co-authored with Archer and Thomas (2015), and he is editor of ''Keats's Places'' (2018).\n\nHe is also author of a historical crime novel set in Romantic London of 1810, ''The Cunning House'' (2015).\n\nHe writes a blog on topics related to Romantic literature. In 2013, he was one of the three English-panel judges for the [[Wales Book of the Year]].\n\n== Poetry collections ==\n* 2009: ''Wan-Hu's Flying Chair'', Salt Press, {{ISBN|978-1844714438}}*\n* 2007: ''The Fossil-Box'', Cinnamon Press, {{ISBN|978-1-905614-35-6}} *\n* 2006: ''Whiteout'', co-authored with Damian Walford Davies, Parthian, {{ISBN|978-1-905762-15-6}}\n\n== Novel ==\n* 2015: ''The Cunning House'', Sandstone, {{ISBN|9781910124109}}\n\n== Critical studies ==\n* 2018: (ed.) ''Keats's Places'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|978-3319922423}}\n* 2015: (co-authored, Jayne Archer and Howard Thomas) ''Food and the Literary Imagination'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|978-1-137-40637-8}}\n* 2015: ''Writing Essays: A Guide for Students in English and the Humanities'', 2nd edn, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-1138916692}} \n* 2011: (ed.) ''The Writer in the Academy: Creative Interfrictions'', Boydell and Brewer, {{ISBN|978-1-84384-278-1}} \n* 2009: ''Bright Stars: Keats, Barry Cornwall and Romantic Literary Culture'', Liverpool University Press, {{ISBN|978-1-84631-211-3}} \n* 2006: (co-ed., Damian Walford Davies) ''The Monstrous Debt: Modalities of Romantic Influence in Twentieth-Century Literature'', Wayne State University Press, {{ISBN|978-0-8143-3058-6}} \n* 2004: ''Keats's Boyish Imagination'', Routledge, {{ISBN|978-0-415-28882-8}}  \n* 2002: ''The Politics of Language in Romantic Literature'', Palgrave Macmillan, {{ISBN|978-0-333-96898-7}}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* 2007: [[Keats-Shelley Prize for Poetry]]\n* 2010: [[Wales Book of the Year]] \"People's Choice\" award (sponsored by [[Media Wales]])\n* 2015: ASLE/Inspire-UKI Prize Essay (with Jayne Archer and Howard Thomas)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/donotmigrate/3668962/Elisions-by-Richard-Marggraf-Turley.html Richard Marggraf Turley's poem, \"Elisions], ''The Telegraph'' \n* [https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/english/staff-profiles/listing/profile/rcm University profile ]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marggraf Turley, Richard}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British poets]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Academics of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:British literary critics]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n", "name_user": "Loveableshovable", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWriter:reference to blog removed since it is no longer active", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Marggraf_Turley"}
{"title_page": "The Look of Silence", "text_new": "{{short description|2014 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Look of Silence\n| image          = The Look of Silence (2014 film).jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Joshua Oppenheimer]]\n| producer       = [[Signe Byrge S\u00f8rensen]]\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* Seri Banang\n* Mana Tahan\n}}\n| cinematography = Lars Skree\n| editing        = Niels Pagh Andersen\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Anonymous\n* [[Final Cut for Real]]\n* Making Movies Oy\n* Piraya Film A/S\n* [[Spring Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Why Not Productions]] {{small|(France)}}\n* [[Koch Media]] {{small|(Germany)}}\n* Cinema Delicatessen {{small|(Netherlands)}}\n* [[Alamo Drafthouse Cinema|Drafthouse Films]] {{small|(US)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|08|28|[[71st Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 103:29--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/look-silence-film | title=''The Look of Silence'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=24 April 2015 | accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* Denmark\n* Finland\n* France\n* Germany\n* Indonesia\n* Israel\n* Netherlands\n* Norway\n* United Kingdom\n* United States\n}}\n| language       = Indonesian\n| gross          = $153,516<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=lookofsilence.htm | title=The Look of Silence (2015) - International Box Office Results | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | date=29 November 2015 | accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Look of Silence''''' ({{Lang-id|Senyap}}, \"Silence\") is a 2014 internationally co-produced [[documentary film]] directed by [[Joshua Oppenheimer]] about the [[Indonesian mass killings of 1965\u201366]]. The film is a companion piece<ref>{{cite web|title=The Look of Silence Website|url=http://thelookofsilence.com/|accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref> to his 2012 documentary ''[[The Act of Killing]]''. Executive producers were [[Werner Herzog]], [[Errol Morris]], and [[Andr\u00e9 Singer (producer)|Andre Singer]].<ref>Ignatiy Vishnevetsky (27 August 2014). [https://www.avclub.com/article/act-killing-sequel-look-silence-will-hit-theaters--208604 Act Of Killing sequel The Look Of Silence will hit theaters in 2015]. ''A.V. Club.'' Retrieved 31 August 2014.</ref> It was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]] at the [[88th Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"88nom\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscar-nominations-2016-full-list-855670 |title=Oscar Nominations: The Complete List |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nA middle-aged Indonesian man, whose brother was brutally murdered in the 1965 purge of communists, confronts the men who carried out the killings. Out of concern for his safety, the man is not fully identified in the film and is credited only as \"anonymous,\" as are many of the film's crew positions. Some shots consist of the man watching (what seems to be) extra footage from ''The Act of Killing'', which includes video of the men who killed his brother. He visits some of the killers and their collaborators\u2014including his uncle\u2014under the pretense of an eye exam. Although none of the killers expresses any remorse, the daughter of one of them is clearly shaken when she hears, apparently for the first time, the details of the killings.\n\n==Release==\nThe film was screened in the official competition at the [[71st Venice International Film Festival]],<ref name=\"Venice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia71/ |title=International competition of feature films |accessdate=24 July 2014 |work=Venice |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006083927/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia71/ |archivedate=6 October 2014  }}</ref><ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/07/venice-film-festival-lineup-2014-movie-list/ |title=Venice Film Festival Lineup Announced |accessdate=24 July 2014 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> where it won the Grand Jury Prize, the International Film Critics Award ([[FIPRESCI]]), the Italian online critics award (Mouse d'Oro), the [[European Film Critics Award]] (FEDEORA), as well as the Human Rights Nights Award.<ref name=\"BBCAwards\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29098103 |title=Roy Andersson film scoops Venice Golden Lion award |date=7 September 2014 |accessdate=7 September 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Since then, it has gone on to win multiple awards, including Best World Documentary (Cinephile Prize) at the [[Busan International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/busan-festival-announces-vision-awards-1201326583/|title=Busan Festival Announces Vision Awards|author=Patrick Frater|work=Variety}}</ref> the Grand Prize (DOX Award) at [[CPH:DOX]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politiken.dk/kultur/filmogtv/ECE2454846/joshua-oppenheimer-vinder-hovedprisen-paa-cphdox/|title=Joshua Oppenheimer vinder hovedprisen p\u00e5 CPH:DOX|work=politiken.dk}}</ref> the prize for Best Documentary at the Starz Denver Film Festival,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodintoto.com/viva-la-liberta-capturing-grace-starz-denver-film-festival-winners/|title='Viva la Liberta,' 'Capturing Grace' Win SDFF Awards|work=Hollywood in Toto}}</ref> a [[Danish Arts Council]] Award for outstanding achievement in filmmaking,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kunst.dk/kunstomraader/film/nyheder/tre-af-aarets-danske-film-udvalgt-af-statens-kunstfond/|title=Tre af \u00e5rets danske film udvalgt af Statens Kunstfond|work=kunst.dk}}</ref> and the Best Film Award at the [[One World human rights documentary film festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://oneworld.cz/2015/awarded-films|title = Awarded Films|date =11 March 2015|accessdate =12 March 2015|website = One World 2015 international human rights documentary film festival|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, the film has screened at the [[Telluride Film Festival]], [[Toronto International Film Festival]], [[New York Film Festival]], [[Zurich Film Festival]], IDFA ([[International Documentary Festival Amsterdam]]), and MIFF ([[Melbourne International Film Festival]]).\n\nOn 10 November 2014, 2,000 people came to the official and public premiere of the film in Jakarta. On 10 December 2014, [[International Human Rights Day]], there were 480 public screenings of the film across Indonesia. The screenings of the film in Indonesia has been sponsored by the [[National Human Rights Commission of Indonesia]] and the Jakarta Arts Council.\n\nIt was selected for screening in the Berlinale Special Galas section of the [[65th Berlin International Film Festival]] in February 2015.<ref name=\"Special2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/alle/Alle-Detail_27164.html |title=Berlinale Special 2015: Films by Weiner and Oppenheimer complete the programme |accessdate=27 January 2015 |work=Berlinale}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Oppenheimer, along with [[Amnesty International]] and [[Human Rights Watch]], screened the film for members of the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]] and their House counterparts, officials from the Department of State, and members of the [[White House National Security Council]] staff. Oppenheimer hoped the Oscar buzz the film was generating would pressure the US government to formally acknowledge [[CIA activities in Indonesia#Anti-communist purge|its collusion in the killings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.good.is/articles/joshua-oppenheimer-look-of-silence-indonesia|title=Angling for Political Action, Joshua Oppenheimer Takes His Latest Film to Washington|author=Tina Daunt|work=Good Magazine|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2015/8/3/the_look_of_silence_will_new|title=\"The Look of Silence\": Will New Film Force U.S. to Acknowledge Role in 1965 Indonesian Genocide?|author=|work=[[Democracy Now!]]|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/02/25/why-an-oscar-win-for-this-documentary-could-raise-questions-for-the-u-s-government/|title=Why an Oscar-win for this documentary could raise questions for the U.S. government|author=Adam Taylor|work=The Washington Post |accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter its theatrical release, the film aired on US television as part of the [[PBS]] series ''[[POV (TV series)|POV]]''.\n\n==Reception==\n=== Critical response ===\n''The Look of Silence'' received critical acclaim. On [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 96% approval rating, and an average rating of 8.8/10, based on 104 reviews. The website's critical consensus states, \"''The Look of Silence'' delivers a less shocking \u2013 yet just as terribly compelling \u2013 companion piece to Joshua Oppenheimer's ''[[The Act of Killing]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_look_of_silence/ | title=The Look of Silence (2015) | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango Media]] | accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a 92 out of 100 rating based on 29 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-look-of-silence | title=The Look of Silence Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref> On 14 January 2016, the film was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]].<ref name=\"88nom\"/>\n\n=== Awards and nominations ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\nAs of March 2016, ''The Look of Silence '' has won 70 international awards, including the following:\n|-\n! Award\n! Date of Ceremony\n! Category\n! Recipients and Nominees\n! Result\n|-\n| [[Academy Awards]]<ref name=\"88nom\"/>\n| [[88th Academy Awards|28 February 2016]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]]\n| \n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[Austin Film Critics Association]]<ref>{{cite web|title=\nMad Max: Fury Road Tops Austin Film Critics Association Awards|work=The Austin Chronicle|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/screens/2015-12-29/mad-max-fury-road-tops-austin-film-critics-association-awards/|date=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n| 29 December 2015\n| The Best Documentary\n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Berlin International Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Prizes of the Independent Juries|work=Berlin International Film Festival|url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/das_festival/preise_und_juries/preise_unabh_ngigen_jurys/index.html|date=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n| 16 February 2015\n| Peace Film Prize\n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[68th Bodil Awards|Bodil Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Og Vinderne Er\u2026|work=Bodilprisen|url=http://www.bodilprisen.dk/|date=1 March 2015}}</ref>\n| 28 February 2015\n| Best Documentary\n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|[[Boston Society of Film Critics]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Critics Name 'Spotlight' Best Picture|work=The Holywood Reporter|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/boston-society-film-critics-2015-846238|date=6 December 2015}}</ref>\n| 6 December 2015\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Busan International Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Busan Festival Announces Vision Awards|work=Variety|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/busan-festival-announces-vision-awards-1201326583/|date=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n| 11 October 2014\n| Busan Cinephile Award\n|\n| {{won}}\